---
description: Logging, metrics, and tracing standards. Always applied to all services.
alwaysApply: true
---

# Observability Standards

## Logging — use packages/logger, never log.Printf or fmt.Println

```go
// WRONG — uses stdlib log; no structured fields; no request_id
log.Printf("processing request for agent %s", agentID)
fmt.Println("error:", err)

// WRONG — uses slog directly; bypasses mandatory field enforcement
slog.InfoContext(ctx, "processing request", "agent_id", agentID)

// RIGHT — uses packages/logger; request_id and trace_id auto-injected from ctx
log.InfoCtx(ctx, "processing agent request", "agent_id", agentID, "org_id", orgID)
```

## Log levels — use them correctly

| Level | When to use |
|---|---|
| `DEBUG` | Developer debugging only. Disabled in production. Never log per-request in DEBUG (high volume). |
| `INFO` | Significant lifecycle events: service started, migration applied, config loaded. Not every request. |
| `WARN` | Recoverable problems that need attention: Redis down (fail-open), retry succeeded, deprecated usage. |
| `ERROR` | Unrecoverable problems that require action: DB failure, panic recovered, auth service down. |

```go
// WRONG — INFO on every request; drowns logs at scale
log.InfoCtx(ctx, "request received", "method", r.Method, "path", r.URL.Path)

// RIGHT — metrics capture per-request data; logs capture anomalies
// At INFO level, log only when something notable happens
if result.Allowed == false {
    log.WarnCtx(ctx, "request rate limited", "org_id", orgID, "limit", result.Limit)
}
```

## Metrics — use packages/metrics, follow the naming convention

```go
// WRONG — custom metric registered outside packages/metrics
var myCounter = prometheus.NewCounter(prometheus.CounterOpts{Name: "requests"})
prometheus.MustRegister(myCounter)

// WRONG — high-cardinality label
ibexProxyRequests.WithLabelValues(orgID.String()).Inc() // explodes cardinality!

// RIGHT — use the canonical registry; bounded label values only
metrics.ProxyRequests.WithLabelValues(
    routeTemplate, // "/v1/chat/completions" — static string
    r.Method,      // "POST" — bounded
    strconv.Itoa(statusCode), // "200", "429", etc.
).Inc()
```

## Traces — add spans for every operation that crosses a boundary

A "boundary" is: an HTTP call, a gRPC call, a database query, a Redis call, a cache miss.

```go
// WRONG — no span; can't see this operation in Jaeger
func (as *AgentStore) GetByIDAndOrg(ctx context.Context, agentID, orgID uuid.UUID) (*AgentRecord, error) {
    row := as.pool.QueryRow(ctx, q, agentID, orgID)
    // ...
}

// RIGHT — span per DB operation; name includes operation + table
func (as *AgentStore) GetByIDAndOrg(ctx context.Context, agentID, orgID uuid.UUID) (*AgentRecord, error) {
    ctx, span := tracer.Start(ctx, "AgentStore.GetByIDAndOrg",
        trace.WithAttributes(
            attribute.String("db.table", "ibex_core.agents"),
            attribute.String("db.operation", "SELECT"),
        ),
    )
    defer span.End()
    // ...
    if err != nil {
        span.RecordError(err)
        span.SetStatus(codes.Error, err.Error())
    }
    return record, err
}
```

## Correlation — request_id must be in every log line

Every log line within the scope of an HTTP request must carry `request_id`. This is automatically handled by `packages/logger.InfoCtx(ctx, ...)` when `reqid.WithRequestID` is in the context. Never emit a log line inside a handler with a context-less logger.
